text:
I don't get to go to White Castles that often. I never get to go to this location even though its close to my work, it's hard to get to during the lunch rush traffic. So on 5/14 I had a chance to visit and enjoy some sliders and a quite lunch before work. Score!

However, apparently the owners or CEOs were visiting that day and the kitchen seemed chaotic. Also when I first walk in I was the only one in the dinning room. Great! A chance to eat and read in peace. Then the place became crowded with really chatty regulars, which served to distract the staff even further. 

My 2 out of 3 of my burgers had their buns crooked, which seems odd for a food that is so uniformly served. They also seemed dry, as in lacking of grease. I'm at White Castle. I want a little grease to help this burgers slide down my throat.  The onion chips tasted watery, like biting into a mouthful of washed onion instead of crispy fried goodness.

I had to ask for a cup for my meal and then sauce because the counter service person just had to keep paying attention to the chatty regular. I felt like I had to interrupt their conversation just to get my food. OK I'm not a regular. I don't talk off your ear about how I've been eating White Castles for 50 years or how I cry every time the OSU Buckeyes lose a football game. I just want some greasy burgers and soda and I'll be out of your hair. 

Impression: Regulars and favorites get special treatment while other paying customer are ignored.  Next time just go to the drive thru.

text: When I learned there was a White Castle close by where I was visiting, I was super excited. Well I ordered my burgers and immediately I noticed this was NOT the White Castle that I am familiar with in NY & NJ. The menu was different. Instead of onion rings, they had onion chips/pieces. Then when I bit into my burger the classic White Castle taste was nowhere to be found. They used these long onions on the burgers. Why would they do that?!?! I thought all chain restaurants used the same ingredients. In NY & NJ and Detroit.....all the onions are small little onions cut into tiny squares that really make the sandwich taste great. Needless to say I had to throw all the burgers away- they were not tasty at all. I won't be back. I thought the whole point for a chain restaurant is to get what is typical of that chain no matter where it is (no deviation). Oh well....lesson learned. I will wait until I'm in NY or NJ to get my White Caste fix.

text:
On December 30, 2014, something monumental happened in the world of food.  Yeah, you guessed it - White Castle rolled out their Veggie Burger and Mike "Irish Green" G. was there to try their three newest sandwiches.

For 99 cents you get a Dr. Praeger brand veggie burger with your choice of honey mustard, ranch, or sweet Thai sauce.  It's vegetarian but not vegan - the patty is, the bun isn't according to the White Castle employee I spoke to.  The burger itself is made from lots of vegetables like carrots, spinach, zucchini, peas, and broccoli.  I tried one of each.

My take on these new burgers?

* The Sweet Thai was really pretty gross, two bites and into the trash with that one.

* The Ranch version was better, slightly better.  I ate half - the rest went into the trash.

* The Honey Mustard one was decent and the only slider that I finished.

So what's the problem here?

* The patty themselves have little flavor.

* They need some more flavorful sauces like A1, Teriyaki, Spicy Mustard, or a BBQ sauce.  Hell maybe even some Franks Red Hot would perk these things up.

* The weren't steamed on a bed of onions like their signature burgers to give them that wonderful White Castle taste we love at 2:27 am.

* The veggie burgers don't get a pickle and I like the pickle.

So all in all, they aren't that good but if they used a smaller, thinner patty, steamed them with onion and added a pickle...I'd be all over that in a heartbeat.

On a positive note:  The Onion Chips were as awesome as ever.
name: White Castle

text:
Ignore the haters! White Castle burgers rank as one of my favorite fast food burgers and I'm not afraid to say it!

Some Columbus Yelpers are saying that stores are unclean. Well look around the neighborhood where your White Castle is located and maybe you'll get an idea of what the inside is going to look like! This particular location is nestled safely away in the Suburbs, so it'll be cleaner and safer than others.

Here's another pointer that might make you skeptics give White Castle another chance. Don't buy anything other than the original Slyders. No Cheese, No Chicken, No Fish. Just the burger with the onions and the pickles. Yum! I'll be honest and say that the fries are nothing special, and neither are the onion petals. A little mayo and ketchup make them more palatable. Barq's Red Cream Soda helps wash everything down.

And let it be know, that I've never had digestion issues after eating White Castle!

text:
As a girl who misses having White Castles in Northeast Ohio - stopping here on our last Columbus visit was a must. And it was great. White Castles have to really be bad to screw up these iconic little squares. We had several and some fries and it was a great meal. 
If you have never had a White Castle they are not like all he other burgers. They are thin squares like 2x2 of meat and they serve them with or without cheese and with tons of griddeled onions, a few pickles and are served on small square buns.  I myself order mine plain just meat and cheese because I can't have the onions. I just love them. My whole family loves White Castle so we often try to remember to grab a case when we head home. They heat up nicely and are a great treat.

text: Whitey Castile's Rectum Rockets, as my friend Sean calls them.  When he says that, I giggle and say, "Rectum!? Damn near killed'em!" This is THE original fast food chain restaurant, dating back to the early days of eating in cars. They serve up tiny little square perforated hamburgers that are sizzled on a grill over lightly sauteed onions, and the buns are placed on top to steam in the meat and onion vapors. If you've never been, be sure to get drunk and then go get some when you are in White Castle country.  I suppose you could buy the frozen product and try them at home but I think that would be like going to Vegas to see the Eiffel Tower.  In any case, remember:  I said GET DRUNK FIRST. Do not blame me if you go without that prerequisite.
name: White Castle

text:
Just for the drive thru experience. I've been to WC plenty of times in my life, so I know what I'm getting. 3 stars because I'm comparing it on a scale of equal competitors.

There's always a swerving of obstacles in the lot and drive thru lane. Mostly garbage, but you never know, and don't want to chance running over it. Example would be the car I saw run over a pretty full warm chocolate shake, that splattered onto his car. 

Customer service is always lackluster. You know the attitude I speak of. From the payment window, where they look at you like it's beneath them to hand you 2 cents change. The pick up window, where they are so quick to close it before you find what you may have been shorted.

The food is NEVER like what you see in a picture. Sandwiches slid into boxes, are often disassembled upon entry. It's usually fast because it's been cooked, waiting for you to order it. Try to order something irregular for fresh hot choices. My recent venture for a try at the breakfast menu did not disappoint my expectations. However I was pleased with the amount of bacon, and the fully cooked quality. Getting it on the toast was as I expected. slightly warm bread. I guess I need to request double toasted. The contents were all in one corner, as if it should have been on a slider bun.

Listen WC is not my go to. They truly got it right when they slogan'd it "What you Crave". I do not visit until it is what I crave. Breakfast was ordinary, and for $2 sandwich, I can keep it on my lazy list with no great expectations. 

I do wonder what the Valentines Day tablecloth and table service is like. I just don't want to sleep on the couch Valentines Day.
name: White Castle

text:
A few years ago I worked for a company with headquarters on Wall Street and had the pleasure of visiting NYC on a regular basis, one of my guilty pleasures was White Castle.

I found myself in Columbus on a business trip and as I was driving to my hotel I spied an exit sign with the White Castle logo on it.  I almost forgot that I was in White Castle country.  I diverted off the exit ramp and bought a bag of the little sliders.  I know that many people think these things are gross, but heck if they are good enough for Harold and Kumar then they are good enough for me.  

Back in Texas we have an imitation chain that tries to copy White Castle, but they don't even come close....would someone please open one of these in Houston.  I know enough people that would make this their home after a night out at the pubs.

text:
Fuck you Harold and Kumar, you almost killed me.

After last call, I told the group we were drinking with that I'd never partaken of the famous burger joint even though I loved the movie.

My sister ordered for herself and added on one burger for moi.  A measly 61 cents?  Why so cheap?

I'll tell you why.  Because it tastes like shit.  Like limp, moldy steamed shit. 

I had two bites - TWO - and refused to eat the rest.

One of the guys in the group chuckled and asked me, "Ever had Moctezuma's Revenge?"  And when I told him not for decades his chuckle turned into a cackle when he said, "White Castle is even worse."

I scoffed.  I mean, two bites...please.

Then, after an hour, those two bites proved more effective than a box full of ExLax.  

But hey, I'm a trooper.  I went to bed confident that the bout had passed and I'd be fine. 

However, White Castle was not through with me yet.  After sleeping for hours, before even eating a bite, I started having another attack of the bubble guts.  

I asked my cousin if it was possible that those two fateful bites could be the culprit.  
"Wait, you actually went to White Castle?  Shit, Libby.  I thought you were joking.  Everyone knows that that place is a guaranteed pain in the ass....literally."

I spent the next hour hydrating and checking for my Immodium and cursing those two guys and that movie that made me think I should have a taste of fame.

So if you see Harold or Kumar walking around, punch those dudes in the nuts for me...they deserve it.

text:
OK. Let me admit right up front that I am no longer a White Castle fan since their CEO went on "Undercover Boss" and sold the farm on wacko, ineffective employee incentive programs after that and raised prices 60% to pay for them.

Whew... what a sentence.

But, really. $6 for a half-dozen sliders and an order of fries? Isn't that about twice as much as you'd guess on "The Price Is Right"? You betcha. Even California prices. 

So why the Santa Claus-like 3 stars? Because, unlike any other White Castle in this part of the galaxy, the guy who took my order was helpful, humorous, happy, and honest. That's the 4-H club, folks, and it's pretty exclusive. 

One last note. Lock your car doors at this location. Remember that really cool dance mix CD I mentioned in another review? Well, I hope the new owners are enjoying it.

text:
This is not the White Castle of my youth that I remember! Growing up in the Detroit area, these "slider" joints were aplenty with the greasy late night food you'd expect. I don't remember what the inside looked like because it's been that long since I've been in one.

If the Short North location is any indication, I'd say that White Castle has overhauled their menu, their environment, and their concept altogether. Yes, you can still find the sliders you may remember. I saw French fries and other items you'd expect at a fast food joint. However, lots felt very different.

As we walked in around 11pm on a weeknight, we were greeted by a very friendly cashier who was glad to tell us about our menu options and to answer any questions we had. The space was very clean and inviting. It was very lit-up like you'd expect out of a fast food place, but the White Castle swag for sale, the heated pick-up order lockboxes, and the swanky menu made this one different from what I remember.

The front window had a row of seats, sort of like most sandwich shops and coffee shops, complete with outlets for your laptops and other devices. The booths and other tables were neat and clean, moreso than your average fast food place.

As a vegetarian, I was most impressed with my menu options. They serve the "Impossible" burger, which is an idea that came to life in the past few years from a newer company- a burger that is not made from animal product, but allegedly tastes like it is... So I'll pass for now. Maybe it's something a carnivore would enjoy without the guilt of eating an animal?

However, they also have two separate other veggie burger options, including one that is a black bean veggie burger. Impressive! This officially makes White Castle the most progressive fast food company in the Midwest! We weren't terribly hungry, we had only come in out of curiosity, so we tried one of each of these. They cost only 99 cents, but they are small. I remember in my youth having friends and family members who could put away 5-10 sliders easily at White Castle. I wasn't up for that task on this night. Instead, my wife and I split one of each, just to taste. If I had gone for dinner, I could see eating about 3 of them with a side of fries and being nicely full.

They were surprisingly delicious, the taste matching that of other chain restaurant veggie burgers. For this price, the convenience, the speed of service, I would like to go here again! I don't know about their meat options, but for a vegetarian, this could be a fun return to fast food burgers.

I don't know if all White Castles are going this way, or if the Short North just has the most upscale White Castle in all of the land, but I think the company should use this as a model for other trendy neighborhoods. If they do, I could see them doing well there, once people catch on that it's no longer your traditional old-style "slider" joint anymore. The employees, and management, and the higher-ups designing this new concept have done this right.
name: White Castle

text:
After a long demolition and remodel, the new and improved Short North White Castle is open for business, and it is amazing!! Spotlessly clean with an open kitchen, you can see how your food is being made and how sanitary everything is kept. They have ordering kiosks as well as a cashier which is so neat, it's a great way to try a variety of menu items. Like the new campus location, they also have "pick up boxes" for online orders. 

Apparently this is a "market test" location so you can get special menu items here that aren't sold at other locations.... most significantly, the famous Impossible Burger! I don't normally like fake meat but I had to try it, and it was delicious. It's an amazing vegan/vegetarian option, rare in fast food (although I also love WC's black bean burgers and I've heard that the veggie burgers are good). 

I'm looking forward to going for a second time next week and bringing friends. I think this location is 24/7, and it does have a drive through.
name: White Castle

4 stars for great service and a major upgrade to the old location!

text:
This White Castle location seems incredibly out of place. My fast food companion speculated that it was probably here long before the surroundings were gentrified to become what is now Short North, Columbus' hip new downtown district.

We literally walked across the street from Mouton, the impressively cool whiskey and craft cocktail bar serving pricey cocktails. The experience felt like a tale of two Ohios: big-city hipster joint vs. classic midwest fare.

But somehow these two opposite ends still offered that polite, midwest charm. We received excellent service at White Castle from a surprisingly friendly and helpful cashier. She even checked in with us when we got accosted by a vagrant who wanted to engage in a conversation about random topics including whether we were "Asian or Chinese." Unfortunately it seems, that vagrant (and possibly others) seems to wander in quite a bit, so this location seems to be the place where you should get your order to go, or make it a quick meal.

The food came up very hot. We each enjoyed four sliders each, and I had a fish slider, two regular hamburgers, and a cheese(burger) slider. The meat, which is so processed it seems pork based rather than beef as the packaging states, is so thin that I was surprised that I didn't like the cheeseburger b/c the cheese slice dominated over the flavor of the tiny piece of meat. I enjoyed the regular burgers better as you could focus on tasting the meat and the greasy dehydrated onion bits. As the quality is lessor than McDonald's, I really am only at a White Castle for the pop culture, kitsch experience.

It was nice that I got two sliders for free, as my receipt printed out a survey code and did the phone survey right inside the restaurant, taking the sliders to go after our meal.

TIP: Order the onion chips. They are like crunchy mini onion rings but way better. A huge portion and surprisingly great quality considering that the sliders are not so appetizing.
name: White Castle

text:
You might be asking yourself, how on earth can a pescetarian be giving a White Castle four stars? Well, let me tell you all about it. First of all, I lived a block from this White Castle for almost two years. Secondly, White Castle sells fish sandwiches, just like they do chicken sandwiches. They're little, they're yummy, and they're cheap. Also, and possibly more importantly, they serve breakfast. The breakfast sandwiches are little, yummy, and cheap. I get them without meat, obviously. 

It's open all night, although right before I moved they started closing inside from 2am to 6am. I don't know if that's still the case, but I was definitely there at about 3:30am a few Saturdays back. Now, here's my secret, one I'm not sure I should be sharing...but 2-3 times a year, almost always when some West Virginians are in town visiting, as with this past late-night Saturday I mentioned, I cheat on my diet. When I cheat, it is pretty much ALWAYS to satiate my White Castle slider craving. People say, "dude, if you're going to cheat, why don't you get a ribeye or something?" I don't want no stinking ribeye! If I'm going to cheat, I wan't the greasiest, furthest thing from my normal diet, and those lil onion covered sliders take the cake. Now you know... =(

My dad was paying this time and when he was searching for his money the lady actually told him to"hurry up I'm cold". That blew me away.  I work at a convenience store I would NEVER disrespect my customers like That or rush them to do something. Next thing she slams the drive through window and made sure we heard it. .. finally a man opened the window who I assumed was the manager. I told him about the girl and asked why she had a sour attitude. I also told him next time we will go somewhere else.  He did not care and told us to call the number on the reciept. So I did.

text:
I'm a West Coast guy so when I saw White Castle I just had to give it a try, particularly after seeing how delicious it looked in Harold & Kumar.

Boy what a disappointment - the N. High St. location is questionable and seemed so run down. Ordered Combo #1 and the sliders are just blah. Soggy buns and paper thin meat...was that even meat on my bun? The fries were gross...the only upside to my experience was they offered red creme soda.

I will give White Castle another try next time at a different location...I definitely won't be craving these burgers anytime soon though.
name: White Castle

text: Four stars for White Castle - yes - you are reading this correctly! This was the 8th stop of the night and I was able to order some great food while inebriated! The employee taking my order was super friendly and was able to get through all of my slurring! The hieroglyphs coming from my mouth were being accepted behind the cash register and the food came out 100% correct! T He burgers were hot and fresh and the onion petals were super good. I remember sitting down to eat and that's about it! The restaurant was super clean and open 24/7. I think this might be the new end of night stop instead of Waffle House. Great job to the staff there for keeping everything so clean and great job to the employee who managed to take my very difficult order! These small steps lead to a great place to stop and eat!

text: It is nice the newly reopened White Castle back in the same location in the Short North with a mixed use of retail,  offices,  and condos in 965 North High Street.  The staff was very nice in taking great care of me. They delivered the food to my table; very unique tray that my 3 cheeseburger sliders and onion chips came in, they have draft beer on tap; and few things that is not at White Castle stores such as Deli Sliders and a 1921 slider with beef, roma tomatoes,  spring mix lettuce,  and other things on a brioche bun. I enjoy Coca-Cola Freestyle with Vanilla Coca-Cola Zero Sugar and Strawberry Diet Dr. Pepper. I will be back at the reopened White Castle Short North again soon.

text:
This is a fancy, new White Castle! 

I treated my sister here for Valentine's Day last night before going to see a show at the Palace Theatre. You can park in the garage atop this location but we were able to get rockstar metered parking. 

It's a White Castle tradition for Valentine's Day to go into fine dining mode. Exclusive, reservations only, paper menus, silky table linens with heart and love decorations strewn about. Their usual counter service turns into table service by the staff dressed in their finest mock-tuxedos. I've always wanted to experience this. 

It ended up being a lot of fun. The "servers" were cordial and accommodating. Even the manager stopped by our table to make sure everything was to our liking (and here I thought that only happened at an Applebee's.) The food was White Castle-tasting of course. 

This could turn into a fun Valentine's Day tradition. Check it out next year with family, friends, a lover or all the above!
name: White Castle

text:
You either eat 'em and smile or you grimace.  Those are the hard facts about White Castle "sliders" and all the other fine little morsels of indespensible fast foodies served up.

Have I ever walked into a Whitey Cassels and ordered.  Oh, maybe once back in college days.  It's the drive-thru that captures all that is Blanco de Porcelain!  You've got sliders, sliders with cheese, death stix, carp on bun and a wider selection of goodies to choose from.... including clucks (chicken).  Double up on the steamed toe nails (onions) and an extra slice of yellow mucus (cheese) and at 2AM the car not only smells tasty... it will carry over to the next day and have vapors akin to an 8-day old unwashed foot.  Heaven, sheer heaven!  Crinkle cut death stix are terrific.

Truly, White Castle food is American royalty food.  This store on Kenny and Henderson has always bagged and pushed into your car window hot morsels of steaming funk.  This is key.  A slider that's luke warm will bring up the night's misgivings if you're not careful.  

Good luck and happy sliding into and out of that drive-thru window.  "Make mine 4 sliders with mucus and toss in a couple carp on buns, puh-leeze!"
